    <h1>FIRE in India: The Complete Math Behind Retiring at 40</h1>
    <div class="article-dateline">
      <span class="article-dateline__item"><span class="article-dateline__label">Published:</span> 5 January 2026</span>
      <span class="article-dateline__sep">·</span>
      <span class="article-dateline__item">{% set author = authors[authorId] %}By <a href="{{ author.url }}">{{ author.name }}</a>, {{ author.credentials }}</span>
    </div>
    <p class="blog-article__intro">The FIRE movement has a simple premise: save aggressively, invest wisely, and stop working when your investments can fund your lifestyle indefinitely. Thousands of Indians — mostly in their late 20s and 30s — are quietly working toward this goal. But FIRE math has India-specific complications that most American FIRE blogs don't address: higher inflation, no social security, joint family obligations, and inaccessible EPF/NPS until 58–60. Here's the real framework.</p>

    <h2>The FIRE Number: India Edition</h2>
    <p>The traditional FIRE formula uses a 4% Safe Withdrawal Rate (SWR), giving a 25× multiplier on annual expenses. For India, a 3–3.5% SWR is more prudent, given:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>India's inflation averages 6% (vs 2–3% in the US)</li>
      <li>No government pension or social security safety net</li>
      <li>Healthcare costs grow at 10–12% annually — well above CPI</li>
      <li>A 50-year retirement horizon (age 40 to 90) demands more conservatism</li>
    </ul>
